            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is magnetic declination?</h2>
              <p>
                Magnetic declination is the angle between
                <strong>true north</strong> (geographic north) and
                <strong>magnetic north</strong> (the direction a compass needle
                points). It is:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>East (positive)</strong> when magnetic north lies east
                  of true north.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>West (negative)</strong> when magnetic north lies west
                  of true north.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Declination depends on your location and slowly changes over
                time as Earth’s magnetic field evolves. That’s why modern maps
                include a declination diagram and an annual rate of change.
              </p>

              <h2>True north vs magnetic north vs grid north</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>True north</strong> – direction toward Earth’s
                  geographic North Pole.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Magnetic north</strong> – direction of the horizontal
                  component of Earth’s magnetic field; where a compass points.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Grid north</strong> – direction of the vertical grid
                  lines on a map projection (e.g., UTM). It can differ slightly
                  from true north; the difference is called
                  <strong>grid convergence</strong>.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Formulas used by the magnetic declination calculator</h2>
              <p>
                This tool focuses on the <em>navigation math</em> once you know
                the declination. It does not attempt to replicate NOAA’s
                geomagnetic models (like WMM or IGRF), which require spherical
                harmonics and up‑to‑date coefficients.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Sign convention</h3>
              <p>We use the common convention:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>East declination</strong> = positive (+)</p>
                <p><strong>West declination</strong> = negative (−)</p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. True bearing ↔ magnetic bearing</h3>
              <p>Let:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  \( D \) = magnetic declination (°), east positive, west
                  negative
                </li>
                <li>\( T \) = true bearing (°)</li>
                <li>\( M \) = magnetic bearing (°)</li>
              </ul>

              <p>
                <strong>True → Magnetic</strong> (for using a compass to follow
                a map bearing):
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\( M = T - D \)</p>
                <p>Then wrap to 0–360°.</p>
              </div>

              <p>
                <strong>Magnetic → True</strong> (for plotting a compass bearing
                on a map):
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\( T = M + D \)</p>
                <p>Then wrap to 0–360°.</p>
              </div>

              <p>A popular memory aid is:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>“East is least, West is best”</strong> for True →
                  Magnetic:
                  <ul>
                    <li>East declination → subtract (bearing gets smaller).</li>
                    <li>West declination → add (bearing gets bigger).</li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>Reverse the sign for Magnetic → True.</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>3. Including grid north (optional)</h3>
              <p>
                If your map uses a grid (e.g., UTM), it will show the angle
                between true north and grid north, called
                <strong>grid convergence</strong>, usually labeled as “grid
                north is X° east/west of true north”.
              </p>
              <p>Let:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  \( C \) = grid convergence (°), east positive, west negative
                  (true → grid)
                </li>
                <li>\( G \) = grid bearing (°)</li>
              </ul>

              <p><strong>True ↔ Grid</strong>:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\( G = T + C \)</p>
                <p>\( T = G - C \)</p>
              </div>

              <p><strong>Grid ↔ Magnetic</strong> (via true north):</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\( G = M + D + C \)</p>
                <p>\( M = G - D - C \)</p>
              </div>

              <p>
                The calculator applies these formulas automatically when you
                enable the grid options and enter a grid convergence.
              </p>

              <h2>Worked examples</h2>

              <h3>Example 1 – True to magnetic, east declination</h3>
              <p>
                You have a map bearing of <strong>T = 60°</strong> and a local
                declination of <strong>+10° east</strong>. What compass bearing
                should you follow?
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>Given: \( T = 60^\circ \), \( D = +10^\circ \)</p>
                <p>\( M = T - D = 60^\circ - 10^\circ = 50^\circ \)</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Set your compass to <strong>50° magnetic</strong> to follow a
                60° true bearing.
              </p>

              <h3>Example 2 – Magnetic to true, west declination</h3>
              <p>
                Your compass reads <strong>M = 210°</strong> and the declination
                is <strong>7° west</strong>
                (i.e., \( D = -7^\circ \)). What is the true bearing?
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>Given: \( M = 210^\circ \), \( D = -7^\circ \)</p>
                <p>\( T = M + D = 210^\circ + (-7^\circ) = 203^\circ \)</p>
              </div>
              <p>The direction on the map is <strong>203° true</strong>.</p>

              <h2>
                Best practices for using magnetic declination in the field
              </h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Always check the map’s declination diagram.</strong>
                  It shows declination at the map’s publication date and the
                  annual rate of change.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Update for the current year.</strong> Multiply the
                  annual change by the number of years since the map date and
                  adjust the declination accordingly.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Be consistent with sign conventions.</strong> Decide
                  whether east is positive and west is negative (as this
                  calculator does) and stick with it.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Normalize bearings.</strong> After any calculation,
                  wrap the result into the 0–360° range.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Practice with a few examples.</strong> Run several
                  known cases through the calculator until the “East is least,
                  West is best” rule feels natural.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations and data sources</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator does <strong>not</strong> compute declination
                from latitude/longitude and date. Instead, it provides a robust,
                transparent way to apply declination and grid convergence once
                you know them.
              </p>
              <p>For authoritative declination values, use:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>NOAA’s geomagnetic calculators (World Magnetic Model).</li>
                <li>USGS or your national geological survey.</li>
                <li>
                  Official topographic maps, which include a declination diagram
                  and annual change.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                After you obtain the declination, this tool helps you avoid
                arithmetic mistakes and keeps your navigation consistent between
                map, compass, GPS, and GIS.
              </p>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ -->
            <section class="mt-8">
              <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">
                Magnetic declination – FAQ
              </h2>
              <div class="space-y-3" id="faq-container">
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    What is magnetic declination?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Magnetic declination is the angle between true north
                    (geographic north) and magnetic north (the direction a
                    compass needle points). It is positive (east) when magnetic
                    north lies east of true north, and negative (west) when it
                    lies west. You must account for declination whenever you
                    convert between map bearings and compass bearings.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    How do I convert a true bearing to a magnetic bearing?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Use the rule
                    <strong>“East is least, West is best”</strong> for true →
                    magnetic:
                  </p>
                  <ul class="mt-1 text-sm text-gray-700 list-disc ml-5">
                    <li>
                      If declination is east, subtract it from the true bearing.
                    </li>
                    <li>If declination is west, add it to the true bearing.</li>
                  </ul>
                  <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Then wrap the result into the 0–360° range. The calculator
                    does this automatically and shows the steps.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    How often does magnetic declination change?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Declination changes slowly over time as Earth’s magnetic
                    field evolves. In many regions it changes by a few minutes
                    of arc per year; in some areas it can change by more than
                    0.1° per year. For casual hiking, updating every few years
                    is usually enough. For surveying or aviation, use current
                    values from official sources.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    What is the difference between true north, magnetic north,
                    and grid north?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    True north points to the geographic North Pole. Magnetic
                    north is where a compass needle points, toward Earth’s
                    magnetic field. Grid north is the direction of the vertical
                    grid lines on a projected map (like UTM). Grid north can
                    differ from true north by a small angle called grid
